hare some pearls of wisdom one week into Trump 2.0. That wisdom, of course,=
 derives from a career in politics during which she has quite
literally seen it all, from working on Capitol Hill for then-congressman <s=
trong>Leon Panetta</strong>; to a stint in <strong>Bill Clinton</strong>=E2=
=80=99s White House (<strong>Monica Lewinsky </strong>was <em>her</em> inte=
rn); and serving as a communications strategist for <strong>John Edwards</s=
trong> and <strong>Hillary Clinton</strong> during each of their presidenti=
al runs, with a tour in between as <strong>Obama</strong>=E2=80=99s White H=
ouse communications director. (She=E2=80=99s also the
author of two books, <em>Dear Madam President: An Open Letter to the Women =
Who Will Run the World</em>, and <em>She Proclaims: Our Declaration of Inde=
pendence From a Man=E2=80=99s World</em>.) <br/><br/>In short, there=E2=80=
=99s no one better suited to make sense of the Democrats=E2=80=99 place in =
Trump Redux than Jen. In this lightly edited and condensed excerpt from our=
 conversation, we discuss the dizzying first days of Trump=E2=80=99s second=
 term, including the J6 pardons, and which Dems will be effective in confro=
nting him.
She also has some surprising words for <strong>Marjorie Taylor Greene</stro=
ng>. You can listen to our full conversation <a href=3D"https://email.puck.=
